EBOLAVIRUS, ANIMAL RESERVOIR (05): USA, DOG, NOT
************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

[1]
Date: Wed 22 Oct 2014
Source: WFAA [edited]
http://www.wfaa.com/story/life/pets/2014/10/19/nina-pham-dog-bentley-ebola/17574217/


The dog of a Dallas [Texas] nurse diagnosed with Ebola has tested negative for the deadly virus. When Nina Pham was diagnosed with Ebola earlier this month [October 2014], her King Charles Spaniel named Bentley was placed in quarantine with Dallas Animal Services. Bentley was seized from Pham's apartment on 11 Oct 2014 and is being quarantined at the Hensley Field Services Center on West Jefferson Avenue.

In a release Wednesday [22 Oct 2014], the City of Dallas said, "The test results show that Bentley has tested negative for the virus. Specimen collection will be conducted again before the end of the 21-day quarantine period. Bentley will be monitored for a full 21-day period, similar to people exposed to the Ebola virus."

The Centers for Disease Control says there have been no reports of dogs or cats falling ill with Ebola, nor is there any evidence that pets can spread the virus to other people or pets.

After a Spanish nurse was diagnosed with Ebola, authorities decided to euthanize her pet dog, Excalibur. But Dallas officials pledged to do everything they could to avoid that fate for Pham's pet. "We are hopeful that Bentley's journey will contribute to what we know about Ebola and dogs, since they play such an important role in so many peoples lives," said Dallas Animal Services operation manager Dr Cate McManus in a written statement.

Pham is recovering at the National Institutes of Health in Maryland. Dallas Animal Services said she is getting regular updates about Bentley's progress.

[byline: Walt Zwirko and Jordan Armstrong]

